  "prompt": "What does the \"@\" symbol mean in Objective-C?",
  "response": "In Objective-C, the \"@\" symbol is used as a prefix for several purposes, primarily related to the use of string literals, selectors, and various other object types. Here are the main uses of the \"@\" symbol in Objective-C:\n\n1. **String Literals**: The \"@\" symbol is used to denote string literals that are instances of the `NSString` class. For example:\n   ```objc\n   NSString *myString = @\"Hello, World!\";\n   ```\n\n2. **Selectors**: The \"@\" symbol is also used to define selectors, which are method names referred to as message identifiers. For example:\n   ```objc\n   SEL mySelector = @selector(myMethod:);\n   ```\n\n3. **Objective-C Object Representation**: The \"@\" symbol can be used to create instances of various Objective-C classes directly. For example:\n   ```objc\n   NSNumber *myNumber = @42; // Creates an NSNumber object for the integer 42\n   ```\n\n4. **Collections**: When using collection literals, such as arrays or dictionaries, the \"@\" symbol is used as well. For instance:\n   ```objc\n   NSArray *myArray = @[@\"First\", @\"Second\", @\"Third\"];\n   NSDictionary *myDict = @{@\"key\": @\"value\"};\n   ```\n\n5. **Other Annotations**: The \"@\" symbol is also part of other keywords in Objective-C, such as:\n   - `@interface`: Used to declare a class or category.\n   - `@implementation`: Used to define the methods for a class.\n   - `@end`: Marks the end of a class or category declaration.\n   - `@protocol`: Used to declare a protocol.\n   - `@class`: Used as a forward declaration of a class.\n\nOverall, the \"@\" symbol plays a crucial role in the syntax of Objective-C, signaling that the following literal or keyword refers to an object or a specific construct in the language.",
